Uncertainty quantiÔ¨Åcation for porous media Ô¨Çows
Mike Christie *, Vasily Demyanov, Demet Erbas
Institute of Petroleum Engineering, Heriot-Watt University, Riccarton, Edinburgh EH14 4AS, Scotland, UK Received 12 August 2005; received in revised form 22 December 2005; accepted 19 January 2006 Available online 28 February 2006
Abstract
Uncertainty quantiÔ¨Åcation is an increasingly important aspect of many areas of computational science, where the challenge is to make reliable predictions about the performance of complex physical systems in the absence of complete or reliable data. Predicting Ô¨Çows of oil and water through oil reservoirs is an example of a complex system where accuracy in prediction is needed primarily for Ô¨Ånancial reasons. Simulation of Ô¨Çuid Ô¨Çow in oil reservoirs is usually carried out using large commercially written Ô¨Ånite diÔ¨Äerence simulators solving conservation equations describing the multi-phase Ô¨Çow through the porous reservoir rocks. This paper examines a Bayesian Framework for uncertainty quantiÔ¨Åcation in porous media Ô¨Çows that uses a stochastic sampling algorithm to generate models that match observed data. Machine learning algorithms are used to speed up the identiÔ¨Åcation of regions in parameter space where good matches to observed data can be found. √ì 2006 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
Keywords: Uncertainty; Stochastic sampling; Genetic algorithm; ArtiÔ¨Åcial neural networks; Petroleum

1. Introduction
Uncertainty quantiÔ¨Åcation is an increasingly important aspect of many areas of computational science. Weather forecasting [18], global climate modelling, complex engineering designs such as aircraft systems, all have needs to make reliable prediction and these predictions frequently depend on features that are hard to model at the required level of detail [6].
Porous media Ô¨Çows, and speciÔ¨Åcally prediction of uncertainty in production of oil from oil reservoirs, is another area where accurate quantiÔ¨Åcation of uncertainties in predictions is important because of the large Ô¨Ånancial investments made. In the oil industry, predictions of Ô¨Çuid Ô¨Çow through oil reservoirs are diÔ¨Écult to make with conÔ¨Ådence because, although the Ô¨Çuid properties can be determined with reasonable accuracy, the Ô¨Çuid Ô¨Çow is controlled by the unknown rock permeability and porosity. The rock properties can be measured by taking samples at wells, but this represents only a tiny fraction of the total reservoir volume, leading to signiÔ¨Åcant uncertainties in Ô¨Çuid Ô¨Çow predictions.
* Corresponding author. E-mail address: mike.christie@pet.hw.ac.uk (M. Christie).
