with the Gibbs sampler ensuring that h(mk) % P(mk).

3. Neural networks for response surfaces

It is important to be able to sample the misÔ¨Åt surface with adequate resolution, yet the number of simulations required increases exponentially with the dimension of the parameter space. There are a number of factors that mean that the task of quantifying uncertainty is less intractable than might Ô¨Årst appear from the demands of fully resolving the misÔ¨Åt surface. Key amongst them is that it is rare for commercial or technical decisions to depend sensitively on all the unknown parameters [6]. There are also a number of sampling techniques, including Genetic Algorithms [3,5], and the Neighbourhood Algorithm [20] which adapt their sampling to the structure of the misÔ¨Åt surface.
However, generation of multiple history-matched models is still an extremely computationally expensive task using Ô¨Ånite diÔ¨Äerence reservoir simulators. There are various ways to improve computational eÔ¨Éciency for uncertainty assessment. Streamline simulators [2] can be used to improve the speed of the forward runs, although it can be hard to quantify the errors introduced. Another approach is to use coarse simulation grids from upscaled models [26], where again an appropriate simulation error model must be used if reasonable results are expected. Alternative methods like experimental design can reduce the number of forward simulation run but have diÔ¨Éculties in exploring complex non-stationary misÔ¨Åt surface patterns.

M. Christie et al. / Journal of Computational Physics 217 (2006) 143‚Äì158

149

In this paper, we examine an alternative approach to increase computing eÔ¨Éciency (reduce numerical cost) without losing accuracy in uncertainty assessment. The key problem is to improve exploration of the parameter space and interpolation of the misÔ¨Åt surface without using numerous time consuming forward simulations. Given a limited initial number of sampled models we aim to estimate the misÔ¨Åt surface with high resolution using a data-driven interpolation algorithm. The rationale of this approach is to identify regions of poor Ô¨Åt cheaply and save the expensive model runs for the good Ô¨Åtting regions of parameter space. The NAB algorithm for posterior inference uses Voronoi interpolation of the misÔ¨Åt surface in the multi-dimensional parameter space. However, there are a number of potential problems associated with this approach, especially if the cost of the forward simulations means that the resolution is limited. In our case, we are using the NAB algorithm with commercial reservoir simulators, and the CPU time for each forward model is several orders of magnitude greater than the receiver function inversion problem for which NAB was developed and tested. This means that our interpolation surface will in general be coarsely resolved.
The above problems motivate us to improve the present algorithm by combining it with an eÔ¨Écient interpolation model to obtain an accurate misÔ¨Åt surface at relatively low computer cost. Such problems are often eÔ¨Äectively solved with machine learning (ML) algorithms. The ArtiÔ¨Åcial Neural Network (ANN) is a machine learning algorithm which is well known and widely used in many Ô¨Åelds. ANNs are data-driven ‚Äì they depend only on the data and learn from them, thus do not assume any predeÔ¨Åned analytical or statistical dependence. ANNs are very eÔ¨Écient at solving multi-dimensional interpolation problems, handling non-linearities and complex noisy data patterns. More details on ANNs can be found in [10].

3.1. A brief recap of artiÔ¨Åcial neural networks

ArtiÔ¨Åcial Neural Networks were introduced in the 1960s as alternative data-driven learning models. Since then a broad Ô¨Åeld of Machine Learning (ML) algorithms has been developed and now unites data-driven and related algorithms: neural networks, genetic algorithms, support vector machines, fuzzy logic, pattern recognition, wavelets and many others. Among the advantages of neural networks are their ability to Ô¨Åt highly complex and non-linear data, from which the dependencies and patterns cannot be distinguished. They are also robust to outliers and noise in data. While neural networks are often described algorithmically, they can usefully be viewed as statistical models with parameters estimated from data [14]. Multi-layer perceptrons are well known types of neural networks. A basic multi-layer perceptron (MLP) structure is shown in Fig. 6. The functional form of the neural network is given by

Xk yi ¬º b0 √æ bjw√∞ctj xi√û √æ i.
